\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12206039 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10033895\charrsid11682795 That's not what they do now?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8727438 RC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10033895\charrsid11682795 
Oh good gracious no. Oh no in 19 - up to the - the beginning of the war before the rent - the rent act houses were charged at an economic rent. And four and six that we paid fo
r our house was about - about a fifth of a man's income at that time. And - they used to - in fact, if I may digress a moment - because rents were so high in proportion to the amount of wages the man got there were always one or two houses in every street
 
vacant, this is before 1918 - before 1918. And there used to be house to let, key at number so and so. And they at number so and so used to have the key and used to be her job to clean the house out after it was empty you see and show the prospective cust
o
mer round and also on - where there were new houses built a fortnights rent was sometimes given. Oh yes. So - houses were - and people - it's not that people didn't want houses but people couldn't afford them and they used to have to live together. It cou
ld happen if say rent were increased to such an extent that people could not afford the rent. You see at one time - today people are entitled to houses. At one time - at those days - it wasn't their right. If - you - it was your fault for being poor.

