I think they both - my father - my father - taught me to question everything, not to accept everything that - my mother was a little more - with being brought up in service I think must have - give her that - accepting }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid739131\charrsid11682795 t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10033895\charrsid11682795 he - yes. She was prepared to accept things as they were. My father wasn't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12206039 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10033895\charrsid11682795 
And what did you draw from that - did you tend to veer on the side of what your father encouraged you to do?
