\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8727438 RC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10033895\charrsid11682795 They lived in Royal Street I understand you know off - by Hill Place.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12206039 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10033895\charrsid11682795 
How much did they see of them - you told me your father saw quite a lot of his people
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8727438 RC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10033895\charrsid11682795 
They - not so bad his two sisters - two sisters and then he had a brother. One time his brother was very ill so he brought him to live with us. But he died. Consumption seemed to wipe out - wipe out an awful lot of people those days. Yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12206039 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10033895\charrsid11682795 
Would you have gone to see your father's relatives as much as they came to see you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8727438 RC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10033895\charrsid11682795 Oh fifty-fifty.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12206039 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10033895\charrsid11682795 Did your parents have friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8727438 RC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10033895\charrsid11682795 
Oh yes. My mother had friends in the street. And when I was very young she had friends who later fell away - friends who she knew before she was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15361118 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10033895\charrsid11682795 . Yes. I do remember one woman who was in the - i
n - service. Mother came out of service. Very, vary vain. Very vain. My father had friends but his friends were more or less at work and they didn't come round the house. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12206039 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10033895\charrsid11682795 Would you say they didn't share the same friends generally speaking?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8727438 RC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10033895\charrsid11682795 T
hose in the street they did share but my father's friends were more or less - of his own.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12206039 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10033895\charrsid11682795 Were friends ever invited into the home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8727438 RC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10033895\charrsid11682795 
Yes. It was an understood thing that people come in if they wanted anything - it wasn't open house entirely but any reason they could come in to borrow anything for that matter or to pay it back.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12206039 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10033895\charrsid11682795 Would they be offered anything to eat or drink at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8727438 RC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10033895\charrsid11682795 
If there was tea on the pot naturally yes. But there wasn't nothing was ever laid out for them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12206039 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10033895\charrsid11682795 It wasn't prepared?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8727438 RC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10033895\charrsid11682795 No, only like in the way of - christening or anything like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12206039 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10033895\charrsid11682795 Did friends call in casually then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8727438 RC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10033895\charrsid11682795 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12206039 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10033895\charrsid11682795 Without an invitation?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8727438 RC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10033895\charrsid11682795 That's right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12206039 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10033895\charrsid11682795 And on those occasions they would be offered a cup of tea or somethi
ng like this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8727438 RC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10033895\charrsid11682795 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12206039 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10033895\charrsid11682795 Probably not anything to eat unless you knew they were coming?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8727438 RC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10033895\charrsid11682795 Unless we knew they were coming yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12206039 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10033895\charrsid11682795 Would your parents go out together at all to visit friends or neighbours?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8727438 RC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10033895\charrsid11682795 They - used to go out together, yes
, yes. You know in those days specially amongst working class people once a person was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid15361118 Married}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10033895\charrsid11682795  they used to give up the idea of going out together at all. And there was always that classic joke I don't know if you heard it during the war - second world war
 that - the only time they ever went out together was when a bomb blew them out of a window together. That's the story. I've seen people walking out together with the husband walking two paces in front of the wife. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12206039 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10033895\charrsid11682795 Why was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8727438 RC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10033895\charrsid11682795 I don't 
know. I don't know. I've seen the children tailing behind them too. Well I - you know the - the - you know that cartoon character in the - in the paper - daily - Daily - Andy Capp - you've heard of Andy Capp. The further north you get, the nore Andy Capps
 there are you know and especially the north east. And - women are only just beginning to get - they are really because they're beginning to work for themselves.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12206039 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10033895\charrsid11682795 
People often tell us that in those days they made their own amusements what do you think your parents did when they got together with their friends and neighbours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8727438 RC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10033895\charrsid11682795 
Well - now - I remember there used to be some friends of ours that used to all sing - one person was reputed be a - reputed to be a wonderful singer and they had a piano - at 
Mrs Stevenson's house you know and she used to sing and - they used to play the piano but I don't think many people did that not in my particular section. I don't think they did much you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12206039 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10033895\charrsid11682795 Would they have played cards at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8727438 RC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10033895\charrsid11682795 I only remember
 cards being played in my own home and very, very seldom and my mother would never take part in it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12206039 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10033895\charrsid11682795 She didn't approve of cards?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8727438 RC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10033895\charrsid11682795 She didn't approve even although she was a fourth -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12206039 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10033895\charrsid11682795 Many people divide society into different groups in that ti
me before 1918 did you think of some people belonging to one and some to another?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8727438 RC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10033895\charrsid11682795 Yes I did before 1918.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12206039 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10033895\charrsid11682795 Can you tell me what the different ones were?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8727438 RC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10033895\charrsid11682795 
Yes. Well we'll take the vicar and the schoolmaster. He would be - and the people who li
ved up in West Derby who we used to go and - Callon - they were rather well off used to have a - horses in a - they used to come to church in a - one of these horse drawn vehicle things. I used to think they were the rich. Well they used to think the peop
le like ourselves were the poor. Now - although I was upset about it and of course my father he used to talk to us about these things -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12206039 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10033895\charrsid11682795 Was he bitter at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8727438 RC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10033895\charrsid11682795 No no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12206039 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10033895\charrsid11682795 He just stated facts?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8727438 RC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10033895\charrsid11682795 Have you ever read the books called the Ragged T
ramp of Gladford. Well if you get hold of that - I think it was published round about that time - well dad did read that. It's not bitter against individuals but it's a desire to change the system of society in which we lived. Some - and - of course in th
is book - it says that everybody would be better off. But that's what I looked upon the vicar and - and accents played an awful lot you know. Oh good gracious yes. More so in this country than anywhere else.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12206039 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10033895\charrsid11682795 How did accents affect you as a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8727438 RC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10033895\charrsid11682795 
Oh - I thought a person with an accent - say now our vicar, Brockburn, I think he went to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Cambridge{\*\xmlclose}, he had a {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Cambridge
{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose} accent. And the schoolmaster, he was a fellow named Ward, nice chap, he was the chap who gave me the Eton suit, I did think they were a
 - a little bit above me and yet the house they lived - especially the schoolmaster lives in now - it - it was very poor when you see it now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12206039 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10033895\charrsid11682795 But you were judging the man and not his surroundings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8727438 RC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10033895\charrsid11682795 No, I was judging his financial position. His ac
cent, his financial position.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12206039 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10033895\charrsid11682795 Money comes into this tremendously?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8727438 RC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10033895\charrsid11682795 Money always comes into it doesn't it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12206039 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10033895\charrsid11682795 Is it the predominant thing do you think rather than the accent?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8727438 RC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10033895\charrsid11682795 I think so yes. Oh, I think it's the - oh no - it is the - what
 he could do with his money. If he con have things he - he requires. And even at that time I accepted it as a necess - as part of - part of the set up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12206039 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10033895\charrsid11682795 What class of society would you say you belonged to yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8727438 RC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10033895\charrsid11682795 Working class - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid5786698\charrsid11682795 working class}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10033895\charrsid11682795 .
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12206039 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10033895\charrsid11682795 What sort of people belonged to the same class as yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8727438 RC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10033895\charrsid11682795 
Well everybody - at that time - at that time everybody who were in my class - people who were overalls - had to go to work in overalls, who came home dirty - who - generally speaking people like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12206039 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10033895\charrsid11682795 People involved in manual work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8727438 RC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10033895\charrsid11682795 Manual work - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12206039 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10033895\charrsid11682795 
What about people who appeared to be poorly dressed but were in a suit - a shabby suit - you wouldn't put them at all in the working class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8727438 RC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10033895\charrsid11682795 Well - shabbily dressed, we
ll - I don't think that he'd be shabbily dressed - he - he would be -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12206039 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10033895\charrsid11682795 How about a down trodden little clerk?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8727438 RC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10033895\charrsid11682795 
Well you didn't look upon down trodden little clerks I don't think. I thought clerks were well off. I thought clerks were better off - in fact I that's why - I think that's why I wanted to be a - in an office. They were better off.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12206039 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10033895\charrsid11682795 
What sort of people belonged to the other classes? You mentioned the wealthy class the schoolmaster and the clergyman?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8727438 RC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10033895\charrsid11682795 The clergyman - schoolmaster, 
that's about all I came in contact with I think in my - in my little bit of a -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid12206039 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10033895\charrsid11682795 What about shopkeepers and people like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8727438 RC  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid10033895\charrsid11682795 
Oh aye, shopkeepers. Well now there we had - round about that time - shopkeepers were a little better off, yes, round ab
out the same. Some shopkeepers especially in a small area and where there's poverty if they can't get a job they will put - they will open a shop of their own you know and they would even sometimes worse off than the people who were - who - would go there
